data.pageText: In Enterprise systems that have BCP Campus licensing, you can configure priorities to determine which End Users can log in after a BCP failover event. This panel is available only if a Campus BCP license is installed.
• Priority 1: These users are always able to log in after a BCP failover. If there are more Priority 1 users than available licenses, users will obtain licenses on a first come, first served basis.

• Priority 2: These users can log in after a BCP failover if there is an available BCP license, on a first come, first served basis. If a Priority 2 user is logged in and there are no free BCP licenses, a login request by a Priority 1 user can seize the BCP license and force off the Priority 2 user without notification.

• Priority 3: These users cannot log in after a BCP failover unless there is an available BCP license. If a Priority 3 user is logged in and there are no free BCP licenses, a login request by a Priority 1 or 2 user can seize the BCP license and force off the Priority 3 user without notification. If a Priority 3 user logs off or is forced off, the user cannot log in again until normal operation resumes.
• This simulation will walk you through the steps to configure BCP campus login priorities for users.
Click View Demo to view the steps for configuring BCP Campus Login Priorities for Users.

- Priority 1: These users are always able to log in after a BCP failover. If there are more Priority 1 users than available licenses, users will obtain licenses on a first come, first served basis.

- Priority 2: These users can log in after a BCP failover if there is an available BCP license, on a first come, first served basis. If a Priority 2 user is logged in and there are no free BCP licenses, a login request by a Priority 1 user can seize the BCP license and force off the Priority 2 user without notification.

- Priority 3: These users cannot log in after a BCP failover unless there is an available BCP license. If a Priority 3 user is logged in and there are no free BCP licenses, a login request by a Priority 1 or 2 user can seize the BCP license and force off the Priority 3 user without notification. If a Priority 3 user logs off or is forced off, the user cannot log in again until normal operation resumes.
